9 Methodological Perspective
A publishable Right-to-Act analysis should not stop at a philosophical statement. It requires a method. The following method is deliberately abstract enough to avoid implementation disclosure while remaining testable.
9.1 Step 1: identify executable decision classes
The first step is to list decision classes that can produce external effects. Examples include account disablement, payment release, transaction escalation, infrastructure modification, access revocation, medical routing, or automated reporting.
9.2 Step 2: define the action tuple
Each decision class is represented as a structured decision object . The representation must contain enough information to evaluate context, target, scope, timing, and consequence.
9.3 Step 3: define required constraints
For each decision class, a set of required constraints is defined. The constraints are not weights. They are necessary conditions. The purpose is not to maximize approval but to define the conditions under which execution is legitimate.
